    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-17T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-17T15:00:00-05:00" n="952"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d952">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/7–1754: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-17T21:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 17, 1954—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 635. Repeated information Paris 82,
                    Saigon 53, Phnom Penh 4. <persName corresp="#p_NK1">Nong Kimny</persName> tells
                    us Cambodian Foreign Minister this morning called on <persName corresp="#p_CEL1"
                        >Chou En-lai</persName>, returning latter’s call described <gloss
                        target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 616.<note n="1" xml:id="d952fn1">Dated July
                        15, <ref target="#pg_1378">p. 1378</ref>.</note> He found <persName
                        corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou</persName> less conciliatory than on occasion
                    previous conversation. <persName corresp="#p_CEL1">Chou</persName> urged that
                    Cambodian government take steps to incorporate resistance elements into
                    Cambodian army, police or civil service. He also spoke with great seriousness
                    and emphasis regarding proposed Southeast Asian pact. He said that if Cambodia
                    were to join such a pact or to permit foreign bases on her territory or to
                    accept American military instructors, the consequences would be very serious and
                    would aggravate the situation with unfortuante consequences for Cambodian
                    independence and territorial integrity. He said that it would be all right for
                    the Cambodians to have French or even British instructors. He made clear that
                    his remarks regarding the Southeast Asian pact, foreign bases and American
                    instructors apply to all three states of Indochina.</p>
                <p>According to <persName corresp="#p_NK1">Nong Kimny</persName>, Cambodian Foreign
                    Minister reiterated Cambodian position that Cambodia must retain her freedom of
                    action to insure her own defense.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
